-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Air Mauritius, Naiade, Produce Buying Ghana Move
-- B y   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 2011-02-10T14:30:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-10/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-air-mauritius-naiade-produce-buying-ghana-move.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed the
most since Dec. 22, adding 1 percent to 2,040.47 by the 1:30
p.m. close in Port Louis.  Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped four days of declines,
adding 0.1 percent to 78.08 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  fell 0.3
percent to 26,605.72 at 2:31 p.m. in Lagos, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index
rose for a second day, adding 0.4 percent to 1,056.02 by 1:56
p.m. in Accra, while Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index  was
little changed at 910.87 at 4:29 p.m. in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Air Mauritius Ltd . (AML MP) climbed for the first time
since Jan. 27, adding 0.6 rupee, or 3.2 percent, to 19.5 rupees.
Sub-Saharan  Africa ’s fourth-biggest airline, said profit for the
three months through December surged almost fourfold to 12.5
million euros ($17 million) as it carried more passengers and
cargo.    Naiade Resorts Ltd . (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
climbed to the highest since Oct. 26, adding 2.2 rupees, or 8.4
percent, to 28.5 rupees.  The company returned to profit in the
second quarter through December, Chief Executive Officer  Paul
Jones  told reporters yesterday.  Produce Buying Co. (PBC GN), Ghana’s biggest cocoa buyer,
rallied the most since Feb. 1, adding 1 pesewa, or 6.7 percent,
to 16 pesewas. Profit for the first quarter through December
climbed 17 percent 8.4 million cedis ($5.5 million) as sales
rose 43 percent to 329 million cedis, the company said in a
statement published in the Accra-based Business & Financial
Times yesterday.  Rogers & Co. Ltd. (ROGERS MP), a Mauritian company with
interests in tourism, real estate and financial services, rose
the most in almost a month, adding 5 rupees, or 1.7 percent, to
305 rupees. Profit for the first quarter through December rose
2.8 percent to 161.5 million rupees ($5.5 million), the Port
Louis-based company said yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
